"""Zechariah mkt-christ — Christological readings for ch 14.
21 verses covering the eschatological Day of the LORD climax.
Key NT connections: Acts 1:11 (Mount of Olives return), 1 Thess 3:13 (holy ones),
  Rev 19:11-21 (divine warrior), John 7:38 (living water), Phil 2:9-11 (universal Lord).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        existing.setdefault(ch, {})
        for v, html in verses.items():
            existing[ch].setdefault(v, html)

ZECH14_CHRIST = {
  "14": {
    "1": "<p>A revelation: the Day of the LORD in Zechariah 14 is the eschatological horizon toward which all of history moves. The NT identifies this day with the parousia — the return of Christ in glory. Paul writes of 'the day of the Lord' coming like a thief in the night (1 Thess 5:2); John describes the 'great day of God the Almighty' when the kings of the earth are gathered (Rev 16:14); Zechariah's opening verse initiates the sequence that Revelation unfolds in its final chapters (Rev 16-19). The 'day belonging to the LORD' is the day on which the Father's purposes for the Son reach their consummation: 'Then comes the end, when he delivers the kingdom to God the Father after destroying every rule and every authority and power' (1 Cor 15:24).</p>",
    "2": "<p>A shadow: the nations gathered against Jerusalem — the final mobilization of anti-God hostility. Revelation identifies this as Armageddon (Rev 16:16), the assembly of all the kings of the earth 'for battle on the great day of God the Almighty.' Jesus warned Jerusalem that the nations would surround her (Luke 21:20: 'when you see Jerusalem surrounded by armies, know that its desolation has come near'), though the final Armageddon of Zechariah 14 is eschatological and exceeds the 70 CE judgment. The Christological reading: the nations that gathered against Jerusalem gathered against the one who identified himself with Jerusalem and with his people ('Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me?' Acts 9:4 — Christ is present in his people under attack).</p>",
    "3": "<p>A direct revelation: 'The LORD will go out and fight against those nations, as when he fights on a day of battle.' Zechariah's divine warrior goes out to fight is the pattern that Revelation applies to Christ: 'I saw heaven opened, and behold, a white horse! The one sitting on it is called Faithful and True, and in righteousness he judges and makes war' (Rev 19:11). The eschatological battle is YHWH's own fight, and because Christ is YHWH incarnate, the rider on the white horse is the same divine warrior Zechariah sees going out. The 'day of battle' comparison ('as when he fights') alludes to the Exodus, making Christ the new Moses who fights the definitive eschatological battle against the enemies of his people.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A fulfillment: 'On that day his feet shall stand on the Mount of Olives.' Jesus ascended to heaven from the Mount of Olives (Acts 1:9-12); the angels' immediate response was: 'This Jesus, who was taken up from you into heaven, will come in the same way as you saw him go into heaven' — standing on the Mount of Olives (Acts 1:11). Zechariah's prophecy that YHWH's feet will stand on the Mount of Olives is fulfilled in the risen Christ's departure from that location, and will be ultimately fulfilled at his return to the same location. The mountain-splitting (a great valley forming east-west) is the final theophanic sign that Sinai's earthquake (Exod 19:18) and Elijah's theophany (1 Kgs 19:11-12) anticipated at smaller scale.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A fulfillment: 'The LORD my God will come, and all the holy ones with him.' Paul's prayer for the Thessalonians frames the parousia in these exact terms: 'May he establish your hearts blameless in holiness before our God and Father, at the coming of our Lord Jesus with all his holy ones' (1 Thess 3:13). The 'holy ones' (<em>qĕdōšîm</em>) include angels (Deut 33:2-3) and — in Paul's expansion — the saints who have died and will return with Christ (1 Thess 4:14: 'God will bring with him those who have fallen asleep'). The reference to the earthquake in Uzziah's days grounds the eschatological vision in historical memory: the same YHWH who shook the earth under Uzziah will shake it finally and definitively at the Son's return.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A shadow: the disruption of the light-cycle ('no cold or frost'; 'neither day nor night') points to the dissolution of the present created order in preparation for the new. The NT carries this image directly: 'the heavens will be set on fire and dissolved, and the heavenly bodies will melt as they burn' (2 Pet 3:12); 'the sky vanished like a scroll' (Rev 6:14); 'from his presence earth and sky fled away' (Rev 20:11). These are not the destruction of created reality but the removal of the present age's structures to make way for the new creation — the 'new heavens and new earth in which righteousness dwells' (2 Pet 3:13).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A revelation: 'a unique day, known only to the LORD' — the eschatological day that has no parallel in the ordinary sequence of days. Jesus said the same: 'concerning that day and hour no one knows, not even the angels of heaven, nor the Son, but the Father only' (Matt 24:36). The day's uniqueness is that it carries its own light ('at evening time there shall be light') — the same light that characterizes the new Jerusalem: 'the city has no need of sun or moon to shine on it, for the glory of God gives it light, and its lamp is the Lamb' (Rev 21:23). The final evening that is also morning — the resurrection day that does not end in darkness — is the eternal Easter.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A fulfillment: 'On that day living waters shall flow out from Jerusalem.' Jesus stood in the temple on the last day of the Feast of Tabernacles and cried out: 'If anyone thirsts, let him come to me and drink. Whoever believes in me, as the Scripture has said, out of his heart will flow rivers of living water' (John 7:37-38). John explains: 'this he said about the Spirit, whom those who believed in him were to receive' (John 7:39). Christ is the Jerusalem from which the living water of the Spirit flows; Pentecost is the preliminary fulfillment, and the river of the water of life flowing from the throne of God and of the Lamb in the new Jerusalem (Rev 22:1-2) is the final fulfillment. Zechariah's two-directional river (to both seas) = universal, comprehensive Spirit-outpouring.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A direct revelation: 'The LORD will be king over all the earth. On that day the LORD will be one and his name one.' This is the Christological summit of the chapter. Paul writes of the final submission: 'so that at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, in heaven and on earth and under the earth, and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord, to the glory of God the Father' (Phil 2:10-11). The Shema-universalized ('the LORD will be one') is the eschatological confession that Jesus Christ is Lord — YHWH's personal name (<em>Kyrios</em>) applied to the Son. The one name over the whole earth is 'Jesus Christ is Lord,' the earliest Christian creed (1 Cor 12:3; Rom 10:9), which is the eschatological universal truth stated by Zechariah as a future reality.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A shadow: the topographic leveling around Jerusalem (Geba to Rimmon becoming a plain) with Jerusalem raised high maps onto the NT's eschatological elevation of the new Jerusalem. Isaiah anticipated it: 'It shall come to pass in the latter days that the mountain of the house of the LORD shall be established as the highest of the mountains and shall be lifted up above the hills; and all the nations shall flow to it' (Isa 2:2; Mic 4:1). The specific gate-names (Benjamin Gate, Corner Gate, Tower of Hananel) give the vision historical specificity; the eschatological city is continuous with — not a replacement of — the historical Jerusalem that Christ wept over (Luke 19:41) and died outside of (Heb 13:12).</p>",
    "11": "<p>A revelation: 'It shall be inhabited, for there shall never again be a decree of utter destruction.' The abolition of <em>cherem</em> (holy war's utter destruction) in the eschatological city is the permanent security Christ won at the cross. Hebrews reads Christ's death as the end of the old sacrificial economy and the inauguration of the new, secure covenant: 'we have been sanctified through the offering of the body of Jesus Christ once for all' (Heb 10:10). The city that will never again be devoted to destruction is the new Jerusalem, secured by the once-for-all offering — the cross that absorbed the ultimate <em>cherem</em> so that the city of God could be inhabited forever without threat.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A shadow: the plague on the enemies of Jerusalem — flesh rotting, eyes dissolving — is the eschatological reversal of the resurrection. Christ rose with a glorified body (Phil 3:21: 'he will transform our lowly body to be like his glorious body'); those who rejected him face dissolution rather than glorification. The plague-language echoes Revelation's judgment passages (Rev 16:10-11: people gnawed their tongues in anguish; Rev 19:18: flesh of kings and great men given to the birds). The graphic detail underscores that eschatological judgment is not merely spiritual but fully embodied — as real and physical as the resurrection of the saints it mirrors in inversion.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A shadow: panic and mutual violence among the enemies of Jerusalem echoes the divine-warrior motif by which YHWH creates confusion within enemy coalitions (Judg 7:22; 1 Sam 14:20). In Revelation, the beast and his armies ultimately destroy Babylon (Rev 17:16-17), and the final battle ends when 'the rest were slain by the sword that came from the mouth of him who was sitting on the horse' (Rev 19:21) — the word of Christ himself. The divine warrior wins without his own army fighting; the sword that comes from the Rider's mouth is Christ's spoken word, which is the ultimate instrument of eschatological victory.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A shadow: Judah's fighting at Jerusalem and the ingathering of wealth echoes the eschatological promise that the people of God will participate in Christ's final victory. Paul writes of the saints judging the world (1 Cor 6:2); Revelation speaks of the saints who 'conquered' by the blood of the Lamb (Rev 12:11) and who reign with Christ (Rev 20:4). The wealth of nations streaming to Jerusalem — gold, silver, clothing — is picked up in Revelation's vision of the nations bringing their glory into the new Jerusalem (Rev 21:24-26), the eschatological fulfillment of Isaiah 60's vision of the nations' wealth flowing to Zion.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A shadow: the extension of the eschatological plague to the animals of the enemy camp — horses, mules, camels, donkeys — signals the comprehensive scope of the final judgment. Nothing belonging to the enemy escapes. In Revelation, the judgment encompasses not just the armies but the entire infrastructure of the beast's power: 'Fallen, fallen is Babylon the great! ... all nations have drunk the wine of the passion of her sexual immorality' (Rev 18:2-3). The new creation includes the redemption of the animal world (Rom 8:21: 'the creation itself will be set free from its bondage to corruption'), a healing that goes the opposite direction from the plague on the enemy's animals.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A fulfillment: 'Everyone who survives of all the nations ... shall go up year after year to worship the King, the LORD of hosts, and to keep the Feast of Booths.' Jesus stood at the Feast of Booths and identified himself as the fulfillment of its water-pouring ceremony (John 7:37-38) and its light-kindling ceremony (John 8:12: 'I am the light of the world,' spoken in the temple during the Feast of Booths, when the great menorahs were lit in the Court of Women). The feast commemorated the wilderness wandering; Christ is the bread from heaven (John 6:35) and the water from the rock (1 Cor 10:4) who fulfills what the wilderness feast pointed to. Zechariah's universalized Tabernacles is the eschatological incorporation of all nations into Israel's covenant story through Christ, who is himself the fulfillment of every feast.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A shadow: the covenant sanction on nations that refuse to worship — drought — reflects the principle that the eschatological order is not optional. The NT equivalent: 'every knee will bow and every tongue confess' (Phil 2:10-11; Isa 45:23) — this is not merely an offer but the eschatological reality that will encompass all. Christ has 'all authority in heaven and on earth' (Matt 28:18); the nations' refusal to worship is not a live option in the final order but a transitional resistance that the sanctions overcome. The consummation involves the submission of all things under Christ's feet (1 Cor 15:25-27; Heb 2:8; Ps 110:1).</p>",
    "18": "<p>A shadow: Egypt's special case in the eschatological regime — acknowledged but not exempt from consequences — reflects the NT pattern that the gospel addresses specific peoples in their specific situations while maintaining universal obligation. Paul's mission strategy was to go 'to the Jew first and also to the Greek' (Rom 1:16) — specific ordering within universal scope. The 'Egypt that does not come up' and faces consequences maps onto John's vision of nations 'outside' the new Jerusalem: 'Outside are the dogs and sorcerers and the sexually immoral and murderers and idolaters, and everyone who loves and practices falsehood' (Rev 22:15) — not a competing city but exclusion from the city of God.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A shadow: the universal principle — punishment for all nations that fail to worship — establishes the universal accountability before Christ as King. The eschatological judgment in Revelation is entirely consistent: 'And the dead were judged by what was written in the books, according to what they had done' (Rev 20:12); 'I tell you, on the day of judgment people will give account for every careless word they speak' (Matt 12:36). Zechariah's universalized Tabernacles, with its universal obligation and universal accountability, is the OT's most developed vision of what the NT calls the 'judgment seat of Christ' (2 Cor 5:10) before which all nations will stand.</p>",
    "20": "<p>A direct revelation: 'On that day there shall be inscribed on the bells of the horses, <em>Holy to the LORD</em>.' The inscription normally reserved for the high priest's headplate (Exod 28:36-38) is transferred to horse bells. This is Christological: Christ is the great high priest (Heb 4:14) who brings all who are in him into his own priesthood ('a royal priesthood,' 1 Pet 2:9). The priestly holiness that in the Mosaic era was restricted to Aaron and his sons is, in Christ, extended to all believers — 'you yourselves like living stones are being built up as a spiritual house, to be a holy priesthood, to offer spiritual sacrifices acceptable to God through Jesus Christ' (1 Pet 2:5). Zechariah 14:20 is the eschatological form of what Christ accomplishes: priestly holiness extended to everything and everyone.</p>",
    "21": "<p>A fulfillment: 'There shall no longer be a trader in the house of the LORD of hosts on that day.' Jesus's cleansing of the temple (Mark 11:15-17; John 2:13-16) was the historical enactment of this eschatological vision: he drove out those who sold and bought, overturned the money-changers' tables, declaring the temple a 'house of prayer for all nations' (Mark 11:17, citing Isa 56:7) rather than a 'den of robbers' (Jer 7:11). The temple cleansing was not an isolated reform but a prophetic sign of what the temple was supposed to be and what it will be: a place of pure worship without commercial mediation. The new Jerusalem needs no temple, 'for its temple is the Lord God the Almighty and the Lamb' (Rev 21:22) — the commercial temple is replaced by the Lamb himself as the dwelling of God with his people.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'zechariah')
    merge_comm(existing, ZECH14_CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'zechariah', existing)
    ch14_count = len(existing.get('14', {}))
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'  zechariah mkt-christ ch14: {ch14_count}/21 verses')
    print(f'  total zechariah mkt-christ: {total} verses across chs {sorted(existing.keys(), key=int)}')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
